com.xilinx.rapidwright.design

Class PIP

  • java.lang.Object
    • com.xilinx.rapidwright.design.PIP
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>

    public class PIP
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.lang.Comparable<java.lang.Object>, java.io.Serializable
    This class represents the programmable-interconnect-points (PIPs) as found in XDL designs. The wire names are stored as integers using the WireEnumerator found in the com.xilinx.rapidwright.device class.
    Author:
    Chris Lavin Created on: Jun 22, 2010
    See Also:
    Serialized Form

      • PIP

        public PIP(Wire wire,
           TilePIP tilePIP,
           boolean isTilePIPDownhill)
        Constructor that handles the complication of putting wire0 and wire1 (start and end) wires of the PIP in the correct order based on if the TilePIP is uphill or downhill, if the wire is bi-directional and/or it is the reverse instance of a bi-directional.
        Parameters:
        wire - The wire involved.
        tilePIP - The tile pip creating an arc with the wire
        isTilePIPDownhill - If the provided tile PIP is from the downhill (forward) or uphill set (backward).

      • getAllPossibleEndWires

        public java.util.List<Wire> getAllPossibleEndWires()
        This method will return an array of all possible wire connections that can be made from the start wire of this PIP. Keep in mind that some of the wire connections that leave the tile are not PIPs.
        Returns:
        An array of all possible end wire connections from the PIP's start wire.
